{
  "text": "First, there was no common definition of a carer used across the studies. Thus the 'carers' interviewed included some who were actively engaged in various aspects of care work and others who were less involved or not currently 'caring' as such. In the main cancer study, the authors acknowledged this by referring to this group as 'close persons' because of their varying caring relationship with the patients over time, although they retained the term 'carers' in the title of the report [8, p. 19] . And in the mental health study [CITATION_1] it was acknowledged that fewer than two-thirds of the people interviewed as 'carers' regarded themselves as such.",
